Here's how to implement all three requirements:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with the back command + dirty tracking

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackAsync);
    }

    async Task OnBackAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
                .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                               "Discard your changes?",
                               "Discard", "Stay");
            if (!discard)
                return;           // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");  // go back
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/swipe back gesture too

The custom `BackCommand` only handles the shell back button. To also intercept the Android hardware back button or iOS swipe-back, override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back-arrow tap, so the shell won't auto-navigate — your command controls it.
- `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()` catches hardware/swipe back. The deferral is required because `DisplayAlert` is async.
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so you only intercept backward navigation, not tab switches.
